    {
      "id": "grammar6",
      "icon": "📖",
      "title": "Grammar",
      "subtitle": "Il-grammatika: doing things",
      "intro": "Commands, the present tense, the future, and the everyday 'I have' / 'there is'.",
      "rules": [
        {
          "id": "imperative-form",
          "title": "Telling someone what to do",
          "explanation": "The command form comes in two shapes: one person (Imxi! means 'walk!') and a group (Imxu!). The group usually just adds -u.",
          "letters": [
            "Imxi/Imxu",
            "Ikteb/Iktbu",
            "Dur/Duru",
            "Ikser/Iksru",
            "Mur/Morru",
            "Poġġi/Poġġu"
          ],
          "examples": [
            {
              "mt": "Imxi dritt",
              "en": "Walk straight (to one person)"
            },
            {
              "mt": "Imxu dritt",
              "en": "Walk straight (to a group)"
            },
            {
              "mt": "Ikteb l-isem tiegħek",
              "en": "Write your name (to one person)"
            },
            {
              "mt": "Iktbu l-isem tagħkom",
              "en": "Write your name (to a group)"
            },
            {
              "mt": "Dur fuq il-lemin",
              "en": "Turn on your right (sg)"
            },
            {
              "mt": "Duru fuq il-lemin",
              "en": "Turn on your right (pl)"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "id": "imperative-from-mamma",
          "title": "The root inside a command (advanced)",
          "explanation": "For Semitic-origin verbs, the imperative is derived from the 'mamma' (3rd-person past tense, what HE did) by switching the first vowel and the first root consonant. Xorob (he drank) → ixrob (drink!). The pattern keeps three root consonants intact.",
          "examples": [
            {
              "mt": "Xorob → ixrob / ixorbu",
              "en": "he drank → drink! (sg / pl)"
            },
            {
              "mt": "Kiser → ikser / iksru",
              "en": "he broke → break! (sg / pl)"
            },
            {
              "mt": "Ħeles → eħles / eħilsu",
              "en": "he freed → free! (sg / pl)"
            },
            {
              "mt": "Kiteb → ikteb / iktbu",
              "en": "he wrote → write! (sg / pl)"
            },
            {
              "mt": "Resaq → ersaq / ersqu",
              "en": "he approached → approach! (sg / pl)"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "id": "present-from-imperative",
          "title": "Build the present from the command",
          "explanation": "Take the command and add a person-prefix: n- = I, t- = you/she, j- = he (plus plurals). Iftaħ! → niftaħ (I open), tiftaħ (you open), jiftaħ (he opens).",
          "letters": [
            "jien — n",
            "int — t",
            "hu — j",
            "hi — t",
            "aħna — n",
            "intom — t",
            "huma — j"
          ],
          "examples": [
            {
              "mt": "oħroġ → noħroġ",
              "en": "go out (imp) → I go out"
            },
            {
              "mt": "oħroġ → toħroġ",
              "en": "→ you go out / she goes out"
            },
            {
              "mt": "oħroġ → joħroġ",
              "en": "→ he goes out"
            },
            {
              "mt": "poġġi → inpoġġi",
              "en": "sit (imp, consonant start) → I sit"
            },
            {
              "mt": "poġġi → tpoġġi",
              "en": "→ you sit / she sits"
            },
            {
              "mt": "ixrob → nixrob / tixrob / jixrob",
              "en": "drink → I/you/he drink"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "id": "future",
          "title": "The future is one little word: se",
          "explanation": "Put se (or ser, or ħa) in front of the present and you're in the future: Se niekol (I'm going to eat). Use se, never sa on its own (sa alone means 'until').",
          "letters": [
            "se",
            "ser",
            "ħa"
          ],
          "examples": [
            {
              "mt": "Ser nikteb",
              "en": "I am going to write"
            },
            {
              "mt": "Se niekol",
              "en": "I am going to eat"
            },
            {
              "mt": "Ħa npoġġi",
              "en": "I am going to sit down"
            },
            {
              "mt": "Ser jixrob",
              "en": "He is going to drink"
            },
            {
              "mt": "Se naqra",
              "en": "I am going to read"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "id": "ghandi",
          "title": "Saying what you have: Għandi",
          "explanation": "Maltese has no plain verb 'to have', it bolts the same ownership endings from the last unit onto għand-: għandi (I have), għandek (you have), għandu (he has). 'Don't have' wraps around it: m'għandix.",
          "examples": [
            {
              "mt": "Għandi ħin",
              "en": "I have time"
            },
            {
              "mt": "Għandek karozza?",
              "en": "Do you have a car?"
            },
            {
              "mt": "M'għandix flus",
              "en": "I don't have money"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "id": "hemm",
          "title": "There is / there are: hemm",
          "explanation": "One word covers both: Hemm ħanut hawn? Is there a shop here? The 'none' version is m'hemmx.",
          "examples": [
            {
              "mt": "Hemm problema",
              "en": "There is a problem"
            },
            {
              "mt": "Hemm żewġ siġġijiet",
              "en": "There are two chairs"
            },
            {
              "mt": "M'hemmx ħin",
              "en": "There's no time"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "id": "word-order",
          "title": "Putting a sentence together",
          "explanation": "Safe default is Subject–Verb–Object, like English: Joseph jixrob il-kapuċċino. Maltese can lead with the verb for emphasis, but SVO is always understood.",
          "examples": [
            {
              "mt": "Joseph jixrob il-kapuċċino",
              "en": "Joseph drinks the cappuccino"
            },
            {
              "mt": "Mary taqra ktieb",
              "en": "Mary reads a book"
            }
          ]
        }
      ],
      "exercises": [
